						               													<description>Makler Gie&amp;#197;&amp;#130;dowy is a Monopoly with a twist. The board is very similar (there is a marketplace on the board). The theme is almost the same but instead of buying properties, players buy shares of companies.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;On his turn, a player rolls one die and moves that number of spaces around the board. If the player lands on an as-yet-unowned company share, he has the opportunity to buy it and add it to his portfolio (there is no option to auction it). The more shares of one company a player owns, the more profit he will gain when any other player lands on the company. There are no houses or hotels in this game.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;There are other places on the board which can not be bought, but instead require the player to draw a card and perform the action on the card, pay taxes or collect income.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The main difference between Makler Gie&amp;#197;&amp;#130;dowy and Monopoly is the marketplace. Every time the player passes by the marketplace, he can go to it. Depending on the number thrown on the die the player may buy 1, 2, 3 or 4 shares. Selling is unlimited. Just before acquiring the player draws a market card which shows the price change. The share may be more or less expensive. It is possible to buy every unowned share in the game. It is not possible to buy shares from another players or sell them. There is no negotiation in this game and the trading is allowed only through the marketplace.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game ends when first player goes bankrupt. The most wealthy player is declared the winner. There is also a variant when the game ends when all but one player go bunkrupt.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
